               <p>ROBERT CHADWICK. I live in <placeName id="t18260112-55-crimeloc321">Little Love-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260112-55-crimeloc321" type="placeName" value="Little Love-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260112-55-crimeloc321" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260112-55-off319 t18260112-55-crimeloc321"></join>, and am in partnership with James Chadwick, and David Scott. On the 2d of January, about half-past twelve o'clock at noon, I stood in an inner room on the first floor, and the witness brought the prisoner in with a gross of bed lace - he denied all knowledge of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260112-55-person401">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MAPPERLEY
               <interp inst="t18260112-55-person401" type="surname" value="MAPPERLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260112-55-person401" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260112-55-person401" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to the prosecutors. On the 2d of January I was coming out of the room and saw the prisoner - I caught him on the landing place, and heard this parcel of lace drop from him; he said he came to inquire for Mr. Johnson, and that he knew nothing of the parcel; he was going down stairs.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. A man said he would give me a penny to go and ask if Mr. Johnson lived there.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260112-55-verdict322" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18260112-55-verdict322" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 12.</p>
